<HEADLINE>
<P>
UCLA'S DECISION TO RELOCATE LABORATORY ELEMENTARY SCHOOL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UCLA's proposal to relocate its laboratory elementary school, as described in 
three recent Times articles (Metro, May 12, Real Estate, May 13, Commentary, 
16), is not driven by plans to build a new Anderson Graduate School of 
Management facility on campus. I have stated the case many times to parents and 
community leaders, but the misrepresentation is constantly repeated. 
</P>
<P>
The move would, instead, enhance the school's research value to the community, 
state and nation. As the national spotlight increasingly focuses on our 
schools, UCLA has an unusual opportunity to contribute to a solution to the 
crisis in American public education. We operate the last remaining laboratory 
school in California. Through the Corinne A. Seeds University Elementary School 
(UES), UCLA is specially positioned to conduct research on innovative teaching 
techniques and other topics that can improve elementary education. 
</P>
<P>
UES, isolated on the UCLA campus, is removed from the dynamics of a typical 
neighborhood public school. Thus, the educational research that has been 
conducted at UES has not focused on the students most at risk. 
</P>
<P>
We believe that the school could better fulfill its research mission and 
provide important insights into public education if it were relocated to an 
urban school environment. That is why we are negotiating with the Santa 
Monica-Malibu Unified School District to relocate the school to the Ocean Park 
section of Santa Monica, where it would be operated by UCLA under a long-term 
contract with the district. 
</P>
<P>
Although the current student population is ethnically diverse, the 450 students 
come from all over Los Angeles. The proposed move to Ocean Park, an ethnically 
and economically diverse neighborhood, would provide Seeds a student population 
that is both heterogeneous and a more natural source for a useful research 
base. 
</P>
<P>
In that setting, researchers could examine the impact of the local neighborhood 
on the school and the school's effect on the community. They could also study 
the role of direct parental involvement in their children's education at the 
school site. Research could be expanded to include other schools in the 
district and students at higher grade levels. The educational achievement of 
UES students who remained in that district could be charted as they progressed 
through middle school and high school. 
</P>
<P>
For these and other reasons, the relocation of UES to an urban neighborhood 
holds great promise for the development and dissemination of new approaches to 
public education in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
If the autonomy of the experimental school cannot be assured in contract 
negotiations, UES will remain at UCLA. Working drawings for our new management 
school provide for the facility to be built adjacent to UES, requiring a 
reconfiguration of a small portion of the elementary school but leaving it in 
place. 
</P>
<P>
I have stated that future land-use considerations might eventually force a new 
administration to close or relocate UES. But the more important consideration 
-- and the one that fuels our current proposal -- is how best to contribute to 
the search for solutions to our national educational crisis. 
</P>
<P>
CHARLES E. YOUNG 
</P>
<P>
Chancellor 
</P>
<P>
UCLA 
</P>
</TEXT>
