<HEADLINE>
<P>
SENATOR SLAIN IN COLOMBIA; VIOLENCE PERSISTS AS NATIONAL ELECTION NEARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BOGOTA, Colombia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gunmen shot to death a senator closely allied to presidential front-runner 
Cesar Gaviria in the cocaine center of Medellin on Monday, part of a wave of 
violence sweeping Colombia before Sunday's national election. 
</P>
<P>
In a separate incident, a bodyguard defused a bomb with its fuse already lit at 
a Bogota school where two of President Virgilio Barco Vargas' granddaughters 
are pupils, a radio report said. 
</P>
<P>
In Medellin, local radio reported that Sen. Federico Estrada Velez, 63, of the 
ruling Liberal Party, and his driver were slain by two gunmen at a traffic 
light. Estrada, a senator for Antioquia province, whose capital is Medellin, 
was a close ally of Gaviria, the Liberal Party candidate who is favored in 
public opinion polls to win the election. 
</P>
<P>
The government blames drug traffickers for the rash of violence before the 
presidential balloting that will decide the future of Barco's tough anti-drug 
policy. Three presidential aspirants have been assassinated in nine months. 
</P>
<P>
RCN radio said that a bodyguard of Barco's daughter, Carolina, defused 170 
pounds of dynamite found in garbage bags at a northern Bogota school where two 
of Barco's granddaughters attend classes. Carolina Barco and her daughters 
Adriana and Alejandra were in the school building at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Wave of Violence: A Colombian senator -- who was closely allied to a top 
candidate in the upcoming presidential election -- was slain by gunmen in the 
cocaine center of Medellin. The government blames drug traffickers for the rash 
of violence occurring on the eve of an election that could affect the nation's 
anti-drug policy. Three presidential candidates have already been assassinated. 
Security was tightened throughout the country, right, as police searched 
passers-by in Barranquilla. Reuters 
</P>
