<TEXT>
<P>
T-Bill Rates Inch Up: The Treasury sold $8.4 billion of new three-month bills 
at an average discount rate of 7.74%, up from 7.67% last week. Another $8.4 
billion of new six-month bills was sold at an average discount rate of 7.79%, 
up from 7.68% last week. 
</P>
<P>
The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors -- 8.00% for 
three-month bills, with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,804.40 and 8.22% for a 
six-month bill selling for $9,604.00. The discount rate reflects the price 
discount received when government securities are purchased at less than face 
value. In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield for 
one-year T-bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate 
mortgages, fell to 8.24% last week, down from 8.36% the previous week. 
</P>
