<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: UNITED NATIONS; 
</P>
<P>
TALKS ON CAMBODIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council will meet Friday and 
Saturday to discuss a peace plan for Cambodia, according to U.N. diplomats. 
</P>
<P>
Officials from the United States, the Soviet Union, France, Britain and China 
will hold the session, their fourth on the topic this year, to try to devise a 
plan for ending the 10-year-old Cambodian civil war. 
</P>
<P>
They are still far apart on issues such as how to disarm the combatants, how 
much of the current Vietnam-backed government in Phnom Penh would have to be 
dismantled and who could take part in any future elections. 
</P>
<P>
Proposals foresee the largest peacekeeping operation in U.N. history, with the 
world body supplying troops and temporarily taking over some of the functions 
of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
