<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND; 
</P>
<P>
FBI RAIDS NORTHROP FA-18 PLANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FBI agents today raided Northrop Corp. plants in Hawthorne and El Segundo where 
fuselage parts are built for the Navy's FA-18 fighter-bomber. 
</P>
<P>
Northrop spokesman Ron Owens confirmed the searches. 
</P>
<P>
"We are working with them in their search, and that is all that I can comment 
upon," he said. 
</P>
<P>
FBI Special Agent Fred Reagan said he could not comment. 
</P>
<P>
McDonnell Douglas is the prime contractor for the carrier-based FA-18. Northrop 
assembles the center and aft sections of the plane as a subcontractor under 
what is known as a sole source, fixed-price agreement. That means only one 
contractor is considered qualified to do the work, and it is not subject to 
competitive bidding. 
</P>
<P>
In April, the Justice Department sued Northrop, claiming the company had 
fraudulently fattened bills submitted to the Navy for work on the FA-18. The 
department decided not to file criminal charges as part of a deal with Northrop 
last February involving a guilty plea in another fraud case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
